nhyMain Stage Speakers
nhr===============================================================================

nhwLee Felsenstein
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncHomebrew Computing Club, Me and My Big Ideas, The History of Hacking
nwComputer engineer central to personal computer development. Original Homebrew
nwComputer Club member. Designed the Osborne 1 (first mass-produced portable
nwcomputer), the Sol-20, the PennyWhistle modem, and the VDM-1 video display
nwmodule.

nhwChris Wysopal (Weld Pond)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncThe Accidental Cyber Think Tank: How the L0pht Forced the World to Take
ncSoftware Security Seriously
nwEarly L0pht Heavy Industries member who helped turn vulnerability research
nwpublic. Part of the crew that testified before the U.S. Senate in 1998,
nwwarning they could take down the Internet in 30 minutes. Co-founded Veracode.

nhwG. Mark Hardy
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncA Hacker Looks at 50
nwPresident of National Security Corporation and co-host of the CISO Tradecraft
nwpodcast. Over 40 years of cybersecurity expertise to government, military, and
nwcommercial clients. Author of 100+ articles. Holds a BS in Computer Science,
nwBA in Mathematics, MBA, Masters in Strategic Studies, CISSP, and CISM.

nhwRichard Thieme
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncI began addressing the human impacts of technological change -- specifically
ncthe arrival of the public internet -- 32 years ago
nwAuthor and professional speaker on technology challenges and the future.
nwPublished eight books including the Mobius Trilogy. Spoke at DEF CON 27 times.
nwHas keynoted conferences in 15 countries.

nhwJohnny Shaieb
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncAxiomatic Events that Evolved Vulnerability Databases
nwPhD candidate at the University of Tulsa (dissertation on vulnerability
nwdatabase history and scoring). Global Delivery Leader and Chief Architect of
nwIBM's Cyber Threat Exposure Management. Over 25 years of offensive security
nwexperience. Created the "Hac-King-Do" framework and co-founded X-Force Red's
nwhacker internship program.

nhwAndrew Brandt
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncBring Me (Back) To Life: Running Early Hacking Tools on Obsolete Computers
nwOver 20 years in cybersecurity. Former director of threat research at Symantec
nwand Blue Coat Systems; principal researcher at Sophos and Netcraft;
nwinvestigative journalist and editor at PC World. Original member of San
nwFrancisco's Otaku Patrol Group. Volunteers as docent for the Media Archaeology
nwLab.

nhwHeidi and Bruce Potter
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncAMA with the Potters
nwBio to follow.

nhwBrian Harden (noid)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncCommunity Organizing Before Social Media... How We Did It
nwOrganized LA 2600 meetings in the 90s. Built DC206 in the early 2000s. Helped
nwcreate DEF CON. Largely retired from the scene. Works on a farm. Writes about
nwhimself in third person.

nhwIzaac Falken
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncThe Persistent Antipattern'); DROP TABLE keynote; --  In-band Signaling
nwHacker of the 1990s and beyond. Associated with 2600 Magazine and Off The Hook
nwradio program. Thirty years in professional computer security consulting.

nhwMei Danowski
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncSubduing the Enemy Without Fighting: Ancient Strategy and the Birth of China's
ncEarly Hacker Imagination
nwFounder and principal of Natto Thoughts advisory firm. Expertise in
nwgeopolitical, economic, social, cultural, and linguistic cyber threat analysis.
nwPrevious roles at Microsoft, Accenture, and Verisign. U.S. government support
nwexperience.

nhwB.K. DeLong (McIntyre)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncIn January 1999, a small group of volunteers at Attrition.org decided to do
ncsomething no one else was doing systematically: capture and archive defaced
ncwebsites
nwStaff contributor at Attrition.org in the late 1990s and early 2000s.
nwResponsible for capturing, verifying, and archiving web defacements. Catalogued
nwover 15,000 defaced sites. Currently Product Owner and Lead Engineer in
nwEnterprise Vulnerability Management.

nhwEdison Carter
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncDigital Hooligan: Origin and Exploits of an Old-School Hacker and Phone Phreak
nwOld-school hacker and phone phreak from the 80s and 90s, active from the
nwmid-80s to the mid-90s.

nhwJericho
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncLife in an Early 90's Hacker Group
nwOver 33 years in the hacker and security scene. Hacker-turned-security
nwprofessional with no degree or certifications. Advocate for advancing the
nwfield and champion of security industry integrity.

nhwJosh Corman
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
nwThirty years in hacker culture. Philosopher background. Shifted focus to public
nwpolicy and the public good. Launched "I am the Cavalry" in 2013 to address
nwover-dependence on undependable technology. Has held AppSec, CTO, and CSO
nwroles. Designed and implemented the CISA COVID Task Force. Currently driving
nwUnDisruptable27 for Taiwan Conflict disruption preparedness.

nhwCasey John Ellis
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncSmashing the (Policy) Stack for... Public Safety & (Not) Profit?!
nwSerial entrepreneur and founder of Bugcrowd, co-founder of the disclose.io
nwProject. Over 25 years in information security. Launched the first bug bounty
nwprograms on Bugcrowd in 2012. Has advised the US White House, DoD, DOJ,
nwDHS/CISA, and Australian and UK intelligence on election cybersecurity,
nwNational Cyber Strategy, security research policy, and AI policies. Native of
nwSydney, Australia; based in the San Francisco Bay Area.

nhwJamie Arlen
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncFAIL: An Epic Career of Doing All the Wrong Things and Somehow Still Being
ncRight
nwOver 30 years of security and engineering experience. Former Contributing
nwAnalyst at Securosis. Blogger and podcaster with Liquidmatrix Security Digest.
nwFrequent conference speaker. Lead author for Cloud Security Alliance Security
nwGuidance V4.

